nhyMain Stage Speakers
nhr===============================================================================

nhwLee Felsenstein
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncHomebrew Computing Club, Me and My Big Ideas, The History of Hacking
nwComputer engineer central to personal computer development. Original Homebrew
nwComputer Club member. Designed the Osborne 1 (first mass-produced portable
nwcomputer), the Sol-20, the PennyWhistle modem, and the VDM-1 video display
nwmodule.

nhwChris Wysopal (Weld Pond)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncThe Accidental Cyber Think Tank: How the L0pht Forced the World to Take
ncSoftware Security Seriously
nwEarly L0pht Heavy Industries member who helped turn vulnerability research
nwpublic. Part of the crew that testified before the U.S. Senate in 1998,
nwwarning they could take down the Internet in 30 minutes. Co-founded Veracode.

nhwG. Mark Hardy
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncA Hacker Looks at 50
nwPresident of National Security Corporation and co-host of the CISO Tradecraft
nwpodcast. Over 40 years of cybersecurity expertise to government, military, and
nwcommercial clients. Author of 100+ articles. Holds a BS in Computer Science,
nwBA in Mathematics, MBA, Masters in Strategic Studies, CISSP, and CISM.

nhwRichard Thieme
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncI began addressing the human impacts of technological change -- specifically
ncthe arrival of the public internet -- 32 years ago
nwAuthor and professional speaker on technology challenges and the future.
nwPublished eight books including the Mobius Trilogy. Spoke at DEF CON 27 times.
nwHas keynoted conferences in 15 countries.

nhwJohnny Shaieb
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncAxiomatic Events that Evolved Vulnerability Databases
nwPhD candidate at the University of Tulsa (dissertation on vulnerability
nwdatabase history and scoring). Global Delivery Leader and Chief Architect of
nwIBM's Cyber Threat Exposure Management. Over 25 years of offensive security
nwexperience. Created the "Hac-King-Do" framework and co-founded X-Force Red's
nwhacker internship program.

nhwAndrew Brandt
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncBring Me (Back) To Life: Running Early Hacking Tools on Obsolete Computers
nwOver 20 years in cybersecurity. Former director of threat research at Symantec
nwand Blue Coat Systems; principal researcher at Sophos and Netcraft;
nwinvestigative journalist and editor at PC World. Original member of San
nwFrancisco's Otaku Patrol Group. Volunteers as docent for the Media Archaeology
nwLab.

nhwHeidi and Bruce Potter
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncAMA with the Potters
nwBio to follow.

nhwBrian Harden (noid)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncCommunity Organizing Before Social Media... How We Did It
nwOrganized LA 2600 meetings in the 90s. Built DC206 in the early 2000s. Helped
nwcreate DEF CON. Largely retired from the scene. Works on a farm. Writes about
nwhimself in third person.

nhwIzaac Falken
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncThe Persistent Antipattern'); DROP TABLE keynote; --  In-band Signaling
nwHacker of the 1990s and beyond. Associated with 2600 Magazine and Off The Hook
nwradio program. Thirty years in professional computer security consulting.

nhwMei Danowski
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncSubduing the Enemy Without Fighting: Ancient Strategy and the Birth of China's
ncEarly Hacker Imagination
nwFounder and principal of Natto Thoughts advisory firm. Expertise in
nwgeopolitical, economic, social, cultural, and linguistic cyber threat analysis.
nwPrevious roles at Microsoft, Accenture, and Verisign. U.S. government support
nwexperience.

nhwB.K. DeLong (McIntyre)
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncIn January 1999, a small group of volunteers at Attrition.org decided to do
ncsomething no one else was doing systematically: capture and archive defaced
ncwebsites
nwStaff contributor at Attrition.org in the late 1990s and early 2000s.
nwResponsible for capturing, verifying, and archiving web defacements. Catalogued
nwover 15,000 defaced sites. Currently Product Owner and Lead Engineer in
nwEnterprise Vulnerability Management.

nhwEdison Carter
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncDigital Hooligan: Origin and Exploits of an Old-School Hacker and Phone Phreak
nwOld-school hacker and phone phreak from the 80s and 90s, active from the
nwmid-80s to the mid-90s.

nhwJericho
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncLife in an Early 90's Hacker Group
nwOver 33 years in the hacker and security scene. Hacker-turned-security
nwprofessional with no degree or certifications. Advocate for advancing the
nwfield and champion of security industry integrity.

nhwJosh Corman
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
nwThirty years in hacker culture. Philosopher background. Shifted focus to public
nwpolicy and the public good. Launched "I am the Cavalry" in 2013 to address
nwover-dependence on undependable technology. Has held AppSec, CTO, and CSO
nwroles. Designed and implemented the CISA COVID Task Force. Currently driving
nwUnDisruptable27 for Taiwan Conflict disruption preparedness.

nhwCasey John Ellis
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncSmashing the (Policy) Stack for... Public Safety & (Not) Profit?!
nwSerial entrepreneur and founder of Bugcrowd, co-founder of the disclose.io
nwProject. Over 25 years in information security. Launched the first bug bounty
nwprograms on Bugcrowd in 2012. Has advised the US White House, DoD, DOJ,
nwDHS/CISA, and Australian and UK intelligence on election cybersecurity,
nwNational Cyber Strategy, security research policy, and AI policies. Native of
nwSydney, Australia; based in the San Francisco Bay Area.

nhwJamie Arlen
nhr-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
ncFAIL: An Epic Career of Doing All the Wrong Things and Somehow Still Being
ncRight
nwOver 30 years of security and engineering experience. Former Contributing
nwAnalyst at Securosis. Blogger and podcaster with Liquidmatrix Security Digest.
nwFrequent conference speaker. Lead author for Cloud Security Alliance Security
nwGuidance V4.

